n2 was forced to -j1 whenever the in-process executor was installed (recipes
run through embedded brush, and parallel recipe execution was deferred). Add a
minimal GNU-make jobserver CLIENT (src/jobserver.rs): n2 reads the jobserver
advertised in MAKEFLAGS (--jobserver-auth=R,W / --jobserver-fds=R,W, plus the
4.4 fifo: form) and draws tokens, so its concurrency is bounded by the same
shared pool every other consumer in the build tree uses.

The work loop runs the first concurrent recipe on the implicit token (every
client may run one job free — this keeps the protocol deadlock-free under
recursion) and claims a pool token for each additional one, releasing it when
the task finishes. With a jobserver present the forced -j1 is lifted (up to N
concurrent recipes; the pool does the real bounding); without one, embedded
builds stay serial as before. Each recipe still runs on its own worker thread
with its own logical cwd, so concurrent recipes don't share mutable state.

